The Abbe Garnier defines a Satire to be a poem without any regular action, of a certain length, either indulging in invective, or of an ironical character, and directed against the vices and the failings of men with a view to their correction. Was satire, regarded in this light, an invention of the Romans, or did they, in this bianch of literature, as in almost every other, merely follow in the path of some Grecian original? Julius Sca- liger, Daniel Heinsius, and Spannheim, have maintained the latter opinion, in opposition to Horace and Quintilian, whose authority has been sup- ported and defended by Casaubon.
